面向跨时段脑纹识别的域泛化方法研究
研 究 生: 王 欣 然
指导教师: 孔 万 增 教授
2025 年 03 月


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
Dissertation Submitted to Hangzhou Dianzi
University
for the Degree of Master
Research on Domain Generalization
Methods for Cross-Session Brainprint
Person Identification
Candidate: Wang Xinran
Supervisor: Prof. Kong Wanzeng
March, 2025


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
I
摘要
基于人类脑电信号的脑纹识别作为一种新兴的生物特征识别技术,因其内在
生物特征唯一性与防伪特性,已成为生物特征识别领域的研究热点。然而,脑纹
识别技术在跨时段场景的实际应用中面临两大根本性挑战:一方面,脑电信号的
低信噪比特性导致传统固定尺度卷积的方法难以适应跨时段的身份特征提取;另
一方面,现有脑电数据普遍存在样本规模、多样性有限的问题,难以支撑模型学
习具有跨时段泛化能力的域不变身份表征。本文围绕有限训练数据下跨时段脑纹
识别域泛化性能提升的核心科学问题,提出以下解决方案:
(1)针对现有方法特征提取颗粒度单一,难适配低信噪比的多被试、多场
景以及多时段脑电数据的问题,提出基于多尺度卷积特征融合的跨时段脑纹识别
方法 MSCANet。通过不同尺寸的卷积核在同一层中提取多种粒度的特征,保证
模型同时捕获短时局部特征和长时全局依赖特征。此外,本方法进一步结合注意
力机制,提高身份识别精度。最后,方法在多个数据集上对所提模块进行对比和
消融实验,验证了所提模块对提升跨时段脑纹识别准确率的重要性。
(2)针对现有脑电数据分布狭窄导致的模型泛化能力不足的问题,提出基
于特征增强与对比正则化的跨时段域泛化脑纹识别方法 DAGCNet。受制于脑电
信号难以仿真,本方法在特征层面引入数据增强策略,通过随机权重扰动生成多
分布增强样本,从而增加模型对未见分布的鲁棒性。此外,本方法进一步引入基
于三元组对比学习的特征约束项,约束增强样本与原始样本在潜在空间保持身份
一致性。最后,对于本方法提出的特征扰动模块以及对比学习模块进行消融实验,
同时进行输入样本长度敏感性实验,验证了所提模块对 DAGCNet 方法的重要性。
(3)针对上述离线多尺度特征静态性与随机扰动不可控性在跨时段场景下
的缺陷,提出一种基于在线可学习特征扰动的跨时段脑纹识别方法 OFPCNet。
该方法深度融合上述方法的多尺度特征提取架构与域泛化特征扰动思想,构建双
流在线协同优化框架。本方法通过最大化原始特征和扰动特征的 Gram 矩阵距离,
并引入身份一致性损失函数,令扰动生成器在特征空间生成身份相关的最远分布。
最后,本文对 OFPCNet 进行对比实验和消融实验,并对不同域差异距离度量方
法进行比较,同时进行样本长度敏感性实验,验证本方法提出的模块对跨时段脑
纹识别方法鲁棒性提升的重要作用。
关键词:深度学习,脑纹识别,领域泛化,数据增强,对比学习


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
II
ABSTRACT
As an emerging biometric identification technology, brainprint recognition based
on human electroencephalogram (EEG) has become a research hotspot in biometrics
due to its inherent biological uniqueness and anti-spoofing characteristics. However,
brainprint recognition faces two fundamental challenges in cross-session practical
applications: (1) the low signal-to-noise ratio of EEG signals makes traditional
fixed-scale convolutional methods inadequate for cross-session identity feature
extraction; (2) the limited scale and diversity of existing EEG datasets hinder models
from learning domain-invariant identity representations with cross-session
generalization capabilities. To address the core scientific issue of enhancing domain
generalization performance under limited training data, this study proposes the
following solutions:
(1) To overcome the limitations of single-granularity feature extraction in
handling multi-subject, multi-scenario, and multi-session EEG data with low SNR, we
propose MSCANet – a Multi-Scale Channel Attention Network for cross-session
brainprint recognition. By integrating convolutional kernels of varying sizes to
capture both short-term local features and long-term global dependencies, and further
enhancing accuracy with attention mechanisms, MSCANet demonstrates superior
performance in ablation and comparative experiments across multiple datasets.
(2) To mitigate the generalization deficiency caused by limited dataset scale and
narrow data distribution, we develop DAGCNet – a Data-Augmented Generalized
Contrastive brainprint recognition framework with feature-level Generative
Contrastive regularization. By introducing random weight perturbations at the feature
level to generate multi-distribution augmented samples and enforcing identity
consistency via triplet contrastive learning, DAGCNet significantly improves
robustness to unseen distributions. Ablation studies validate the critical roles of
feature perturbation and contrastive learning modules.
(3) Recognizing the limitations of static multi-scale features and uncontrolled
random perturbations in cross-session applications, we propose OFPCNet – an
Online Feature Perturbation Contrastive Network for brainprint recognition. This
architecture synergistically integrates multi-scale feature extraction with domain


杭州电子科技大学硕士学位论文
III
generalization principles through a dual-stream co-optimization framework. By
maximizing the Gram matrix distance between original and perturbed features while
preserving identity consistency through adversarial optimization, OFPCNet achieves
domain-invariant feature representation. Comparative experiments and sensitivity
analyses confirm its effectiveness in enhancing cross-session robustness.
Keywords: Deep learning, Brainprint identification, Domain generalization, Data
augmentation, Contrastive learning


